 and legislators’Dedicates a chapter to each section, each including a preview, a summary of sections and a reviewHelpful student features include chronology, a glossary of key terms and a guide to further readingAdopting an interpretative approach throughout, Daniel Conway treats Beyond Good and Evil as a coherent, unified and carefully crafted complete text. When treated this way, the text reveals itself as a guide to the education that Nietzsche prescribes for his best readers, at the brink of the new, post-moral era. Conway makes sense of the overarching aims and structure of the book at the same time as providing a broader context for the arguments Nietzsche makes and the positions he stakes out. Requiring no prior knowledge of the text or of Nietzsche, he guides you through the text with the reward of a more developed reading of the distinctly political agenda that emerges in the second half of Beyond Good and Evil.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079765740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147443547540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474435475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474435475/original  a978-3-11-079765-7  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles